ne 108 |\n| **Important** | Performance is not guaranteed for adversarial inputs with many free variables (toggle: weight enumeration is C(n,k); counter: exponential in modulus^numFree) | Lines 138-159, 283-336 |\n| **Suggestion** | `pivotAccum.slice()` at each recursion level could be replaced with undo-on-backtrack for better performance | Line 308 |\n| **Suggestion** | Add a comment explaining why `bestResult ?? []` at line 161 is unreachable in practice | Line 161 |\n| **Suggestion** | Add defensive comment or assertion on `modInverse` noting it requires prime modulus | Line 362 |\n| **Suggestion** | Consider adding input validation (e.g., light indices within bounds, modulus > 1) for robustness | General |\n\n### Recommended Fix for the 32-bit Overflow Issue\n\nThe most impactful fix is addressing the 32-bit overflow at `/workspace/src/index.ts` lines 108 and 155. Here is a sketch of the fix:\n\nIn `computeAndUpdate`, change `mask` parameter to `bigint` (or use BigInt throughout):\n\n```typescript\n// Replace line 108:\nif ((mask >> k) & 1) {\n// With:\nif ((bigMask >> BigInt(k)) & 1n) {\n```\n\nIn the `numFree > 25` branch, use BigInt for the mask:\n\n```typescript\nconst enumByWeight = (pos: number, start: number, mask: bigint): void => {\n    if (pos === w) {\n        computeAndUpdate(mask, w);\n        return;\n    }\n    for (let i = start; i < numFree; i++) {\n        enumByWeight(pos + 1, i + 1, mask | (1n << BigInt(i)));\n    }\n};\nenumByWeight(0, 0, 0n);\n```\n\nThis ensures correctness for up to 40+ free variables.\n\n### Verdict\n\nThe implementation is fundamentally sound. The Gaussian elimination is correct in both GF(2) and GF(p). The optimization logic (minimum weight/total with lex tiebreaking) is correct. The test suite covers the core cases well. The primary actionable concern is the 32-bit integer overflow when `numFree >= 31`, which should be fixed to meet the stated constraint of up to 40 buttons and 40 lights. The performance concern abou